</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD10FD52DD3AFF8741F8D7D2FAD3861A" blockId="2.[151,1436,1084,2009]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,1328]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="149" pageId="2" pageNumber="148">
Hutchings and Glasby (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF8640EED7D2FDB58192" box="[465,524,1695,1719]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="1986.0">1986</number>
) expanded the generic definition to include species with notopodia beginning on segments 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF864039D789FEAD81F9" box="[262,276,1732,1756]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="2.0">2</number>
or 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF864008D789FEFC81F9" box="[311,325,1732,1756]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="3.0">3</number>
(Hutching &amp; Glasby 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF86430AD789FDC981F9" box="[565,624,1732,1756]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="1986.0">1986</number>
; Glasby &amp; Glasby 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF86427CD789FC3981F9" box="[835,896,1732,1756]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="2006.0">2006</number>
). In addition, the authors discussed the problems in counting the anterior segments of some taxa. However, according to Nogueira 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3AFF86450DD7A4FBD58025" box="[1074,1132,1768,1792]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="148">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF864543D7AAFB0081DA" box="[1148,1209,1767,1791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="2010.0">2010</number>
), in all polycirrines, notopodia, if present, start from segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF86435BD641FDCD8001" box="[612,628,1804,1828]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="3.0">3</number>
, and those taxa diagnosed as having notopodia from a different segment are due to miscountings of anterior segments. Nogueira 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3AFF864238D67CFC86806D" box="[775,831,1840,1864]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="148">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF864272D662FC318062" box="[845,904,1839,1863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="2010.0">2010</number>
) also indicated that polycirrines are remarkably conservative with regard to their anterior end and in all taxa of this subfamily the basal part of prostomium may terminate laterally or extend ventrally and terminate between mid-ventral glandular shields on segments 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF864401D63AFAF580AA" box="[1342,1356,1911,1935]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="1.0">1</number>
and 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF8644B9D63AFA2E80AA" box="[1414,1431,1911,1935]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="2.0">2</number>
; the upper lip is large, nearly circular, while the lower lip is button-like, frequently covered by mid-ventral glandular shield on segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF864047D68DFE3E80FD" box="[376,391,1984,2008]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="1.0">1</number>
; segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3AFF86433CD68DFDA880FD" box="[515,529,1984,2008]" pageId="2" pageNumber="148" value="1.0">1</number>
is well developed at least ventrally, with large mid-ventral glandular shield; segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8741C4D1DAFEB0878A" box="[251,265,151,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
is always distinctly narrower than other segments, constricting the body posteriorly to the mouth; a midventral glandular shield may be present on segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8743D4D1F1FD4287F1" box="[747,763,188,212]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
, or fused to segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8742CDD1F1FBB887F1" box="[1010,1025,188,212]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
; a mid-ventral groove extends from segments 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874039D192FE8A87D2" box="[262,307,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
; and notopodia, if present, begin from segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874275D192FCE387D2" box="[842,858,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="3.0">3</number>
. The miscounting of anterior segments, which have caused some authors to consider notopodia as beginning on segments 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8742D6D049FC4E8639" box="[1001,1015,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
or 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874515D049FB818639" box="[1066,1080,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="4.0">4</number>
(Hessle 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874598D049FB5B8639" box="[1191,1250,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1917.0">1917</number>
; Holthe 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874471D049FA308639" box="[1358,1417,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1986.0">1986</number>
b; Hutchings &amp; Glasby 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8740BBD06AFE07861A" box="[388,446,295,319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1986.0">1986</number>
) is probably due to the peristomium and segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8742D1D06AFC45861A" box="[1006,1020,295,319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
either extending dorsally or not.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD10FD52DD3BFF8741F8D000FE0C8689" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">
In the present paper we have reconsidered our interpretation of the lower lip and segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87458FD001FB078641" box="[1200,1214,332,356]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
, and considered the large midventral shield posterior to mouth as the lower lip, instead of segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874523D022FB9386A2" box="[1052,1066,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
, as discussed in more details by Nogueira 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874039D0D8FE878689" box="[262,318,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">et al.</emphasis>
(in press).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD10FD52DD3BFF8741F8D0FAFDFF8412" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">
Glasby and Glasby (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87408DD0FAFE4986EA" box="[434,496,439,463]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2006.0">2006</number>
), through a morphometric analysis, recognized two 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF874576D0F5FB3C86F5" box="[1097,1157,440,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">types</typeStatus>
of uncini in 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF874423D0F5FA2C86F5" box="[1308,1429,440,464]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874423D0F5FA2C86F5" box="[1308,1429,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Polycirrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF8741A8D090FF6986D0" box="[151,208,477,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8741E7D091FF5F86D1" box="[216,230,476,500]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
uncini 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874001D090FEC786D1" box="[318,382,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">sensu</emphasis>
Glasby and Glasby (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87434DD091FD1786D1" box="[626,686,476,500]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2006.0">2006</number>
) are distinctly longer than high, with a flat base, short triangular heel directed posteriorly, short back, with short to inconspicuous dorsal button placed closer to main fang base than to tip of elongated prow. 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF8740CCD368FD958518" box="[499,556,549,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87430CD369FDF88519" box="[563,577,548,572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
uncini are about as long as high and also have an almost straight base and elongate prow, but the heel is elongate, directed downwards, and the back is also elongate, while the dorsal button is similar to that of 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF8740DED320FDAB85A0" box="[481,530,621,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874321D321FD9585A1" box="[542,556,620,644]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
uncini, short to inconspicuous, situated near base of main fang (see also Nogueira 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874035D3DCFEFC858D" box="[266,325,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874071D3C2FE358582" box="[334,396,655,679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2010.0">2010</number>
). Moreover, our SEMs show that 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF874228D3DDFCF0858D" box="[791,841,656,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87426ED3C2FCE68582" box="[849,863,655,679]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
uncini are embedded in neuropodia like those of the other subfamilies of 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF8740F9D3F9FDEF85E9" box="[454,598,692,716]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="family">Terebellidae</taxonomicName>
, only the main fang and the crest extending off the integument, the remaining uncinial parts being internal (
<figureCitation id="5594E1D7DD3BFF87435CD39AFD1285CA" box="[611,683,727,751]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,250,961,984]" captionTargetBox="[152,1432,194,937]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,193,941]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. Polycirrus papillosus sp. nov. Photos A – C, E from holotype (MZUSP 1216); photos D, F – G from paratype 10 (MZUSP 1244). A, notochaetae from anterior notopodium; B, close up view of the tips of two notochaetae from anterior row (winged); C – E, uncini, anterior neuropodium; F – G, uncini, posterior neuropodia; arrow points to dorsal button. Scale bars: A – C = 20 μm; D, G = 5 μm; E = 10 μm; F = 2 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218721/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">
Figs 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8743A2D39AFD1285CA" box="[669,683,727,751]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
C–G; 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8743CFD39AFD4485CA" box="[752,765,727,751]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="8.0">8</number>
F–G), while 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF8742AFD394FC7885D4" box="[912,961,729,753]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8742F7D39AFC6F85CA" box="[968,982,727,751]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
uncini are more exposed, with only the anterior third to half of the prow covered by thin epithelium, while part of the base is visible, sitting on top of neuropodial pinnules (
<figureCitation id="5594E1D7DD3BFF8740A7D252FE528412" box="[408,491,799,823]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1232,1255]" captionTargetBox="[152,1433,197,1209]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,195,1211]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 10. Polycirrus habitats sp. nov. Photos A – D, F from holotype (MZUSP 1221); photos E, G – I from paratype 1 (MZUSP 1246). A – B, tips of pinnate notochaetae; C – D, F – I, uncini, posterior neuropodia; E, notochaetae, anterior notopodium. Scale bars: A, C = 20 μm; B, D, F = 10 μm; E, G – I = 10 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/218725/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">
Fig. 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8740F1D252FE528412" box="[462,491,799,823]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
D, F–I).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD10FD52DD3BFF8741F8D209FEE58311" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">
Glasby and Glasby (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8740FFD209FE428479" box="[448,507,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2006.0">2006</number>
) found a correlation between the morphology of uncini and other characters traditionally considered important in the taxonomy of the group, especially the last segment with notopodia and the presence of pinnate notochaetae. According to them, the species with 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF87429CD2C0FC6A8480" box="[931,979,909,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8742E5D2C1FC518481" box="[986,1000,908,932]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
uncini can be divided into two groups, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8741A8D2E2FF1884E2" box="[151,161,943,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
A and 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8741C5D2E2FEBC84E2" box="[250,261,943,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.0">1</number>
B, depending on the position of the last pair of notopodia, if up to segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87459ED2E2FB7984E2" box="[1185,1216,943,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="20.0">20</number>
, or posterior to it, respectively. On the other hand, all species with 
<typeStatus id="121443F0DD3BFF8743F6D298FD4084C8" box="[713,761,981,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">type</typeStatus>
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87423CD299FCA884C9" box="[771,785,980,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
uncini have the last pair of notopodia on segment 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874460D299FAC284C9" box="[1375,1403,980,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="20.0">20</number>
or before that, and they are divided into groups 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8743B0D2BAFD25832A" box="[655,668,1015,1039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
A and 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8743D8D2BAFD4C832A" box="[743,757,1015,1039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2.0">2</number>
B by bearing or lacking pinnate notochaetae, respectively, in the posterior row.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD10FD52DD3BFF8741F8D572FE418215" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">
Nine species of 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF8740BDD50DFE41837D" box="[386,504,1088,1112]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF8740BDD50DFE41837D" box="[386,504,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Polycirrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been recorded from the Brazilian coast, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF874531D50CFA958372" authority="Garraffoni" authorityName="Garraffoni" box="[1038,1324,1087,1112]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abrolhensis">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874531D50CFB17837D" box="[1038,1198,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P. abrolhensis</emphasis>
Garraffoni
</taxonomicName>
&amp; Costa, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8741A8D529FF6B8359" box="[151,210,1124,1148]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2003.0">2003</number>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF8741E2D528FDAA8359" authority="Kinberg, 1866" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1866" box="[221,531,1124,1148]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF8741E2D528FEEC8359" box="[221,341,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P. clavatus</emphasis>
(Kinberg, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8740F0D529FDB28359" box="[463,523,1124,1148]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1866.0">1866</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF874321D528FCCA8359" authority="Grube, 1870" authorityName="Grube" authorityYear="1870" box="[542,883,1124,1148]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="coccineus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874321D528FD898359" box="[542,560,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874362D528FD728359" box="[605,715,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">coccineus</emphasis>
(Grube, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87420FD529FCD58359" box="[816,876,1124,1148]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1870.0">1870</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF874240D528FB0B8359" authority="Benham, 1921" authorityName="Benham" authorityYear="1921" box="[895,1202,1124,1148]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hamiltoni">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874240D528FBBF8359" box="[895,1030,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P. hamiltoni</emphasis>
Benham, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874547D529FB0B8359" box="[1144,1202,1124,1148]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1921.0">1921</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF874581D528FA258359" authority="Garraffoni" authorityName="Garraffoni" box="[1214,1436,1124,1148]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="paivai">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874581D528FAA68359" box="[1214,1311,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P. paivai</emphasis>
Garraffoni
</taxonomicName>
&amp; Costa, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874036D5CAFEFD83BA" box="[265,324,1159,1183]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2003.0">2003</number>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF87406CD5C4FD0483BA" authority="Wollebaek, 1912" authorityName="Wollebaek" authorityYear="1912" box="[339,701,1159,1184]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="plumosus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF87406CD5C4FE648385" box="[339,477,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P. plumosus</emphasis>
(Wollebaek, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874345D5CAFD0F83BA" box="[634,694,1159,1183]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1912.0">1912</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF8743F2D5C4FB8883BA" authority="Langerhans, 1881" authorityName="Langerhans" authorityYear="1881" box="[717,1073,1159,1184]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tenuisetis">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF8743F2D5C4FCEE8385" box="[717,855,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">P. tenuisetis</emphasis>
Langerhans, 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8742C9D5CAFB8883BA" box="[1014,1073,1159,1183]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1881.0">1881</number>
</taxonomicName>
, and two informally described, 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF8741A8D5E1FEB483E1" box="[151,269,1196,1220]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF8741A8D5E1FEB483E1" box="[151,269,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Polycirrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874077D5E0FE3E83E1" box="[328,391,1197,1220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">sensu</emphasis>
Alves (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF8740D4D5E1FD9F83E1" box="[491,550,1196,1220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2008.0">2008</number>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="0AAF86D1DD3BFF87434DD5E1FD5183E1" box="[626,744,1196,1220]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF87434DD5E1FD5183E1" box="[626,744,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Polycirrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. A 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874279D5E0FC3D83E1" box="[838,900,1197,1220]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">sensu</emphasis>
Blankensteyn (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87457ED5E1FBC283E1" box="[1089,1147,1196,1220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1988.0">1988</number>
). In 
<tableCitation id="802DC8E9DD3BFF874582D5E1FA8483E1" box="[1213,1341,1196,1220]" captionStart-0="TABLE 1" captionStart-1="TABLE 2" captionStartId-0="4.[125,211,518,541]" captionStartId-1="10.[151,239,1159,1183]" captionTargetBox-0="[139,1873,697,1546]" captionTargetBox-1="[160,1422,1248,1945]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="10" captionText-0="TABLE 1. List of species of Polycirrus used for comparison with the species described in this paper, with the main morphological characters used for the identification. Taxa already recorded for Brazilian waters are marked with a “ * ”; (-) unknown or not observed. Sources: Kinberg (1866); Hessle (1917); Hutchings and Murray (1984); Hutching and Glasby (1986); Hutchings (1993); Glasby and Glasby (2006); characters of Polycirrus abrolhensis, P. bicrinalis, P. glaucus, P. paivai, and P. variabilis examined on type-material." captionText-1="TABLE 2. Comparison between the species of Polycirrus described in this paper, with the main morphological characters used in the identification. (-) unknown or not observed." httpUri-0="http://table.plazi.org/id/99D0ADDADD3CFF804142D34BFE238552" httpUri-1="http://table.plazi.org/id/99D0ADDADD32FF8E41A8D5CAFCE1839A" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" tableUuid-0="99D0ADDADD3CFF804142D34BFE238552" tableUuid-1="99D0ADDADD32FF8E41A8D5CAFCE1839A">
Tables 
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF87442CD5E1FA8483E1" box="[1299,1341,1196,1220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</tableCitation>
species described in the present study are compared with the most similar congeners belonging to the same groups 
<emphasis id="FFDB2140DD3BFF874461D59CFA2583CD" box="[1374,1436,1233,1256]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">sensu</emphasis>
Glasby and Glasby (
<number id="7B67EF75DD3BFF874044D5B9FE018229" box="[379,440,1268,1292]" pageId="3" pageNumber="149" value="2006.0">2006</number>
), and all species recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="B5B8BDC2DD3BFF874223D5B9FCDA8229" box="[796,867,1268,1292]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="149">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, regardless of the group they belong to, and if they were formally described or not.
</paragraph>
